<h2 id="when-to-roll-back">When to roll back</h2>

<p>The rule: <strong>any incident affecting real users is grounds for an immediate one-level rollback</strong>. Examples:</p>

<ul>
    <li>Support tickets about missing password resets.</li>
    <li>A spike in <code>quarantine</code> or <code>reject</code> dispositions for a known internal sender.</li>
    <li>A drop in deliverability in Postmaster Tools.</li>
    <li>A new vendor onboarded mid-migration without DKIM setup &mdash; their mail is now failing.</li>
</ul>

<p>Roll back, fix, and resume. Don't try to push through &mdash; the goal is to reach <code>p=reject</code> sustainably, not to hit a deadline.</p>

<p>What "roll back" means in practice:</p>

<ol>
    <li>At <code>p=reject; pct=25</code> with an incident &rarr; drop to <code>p=quarantine; pct=100</code>.</li>
    <li>At <code>p=quarantine; pct=50</code> with an incident &rarr; drop to <code>p=quarantine; pct=10</code>.</li>
    <li>Major incident at any phase &rarr; drop straight to <code>p=none</code>, investigate, then re-enter from Phase 2 (you don't need to redo Phase 1).</li>
</ol>

<p>Because TTL on the DMARC record is short, the rollback propagates in minutes &mdash; not hours.</p>

<h2 id="how-sendvery-helps">How Sendvery surfaces these signals</h2>

<p>The whole migration depends on visibility into your aggregate reports &mdash; which IPs are passing, which are failing, what their alignment looks like, and how the trend is moving. That's exactly what Sendvery does:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Auto-ingests aggregate reports</strong> from a dedicated reporting mailbox &mdash; no manual XML parsing.</li>
    <li><strong>Maps source IPs to senders</strong> using RDAP and known-vendor heuristics, so you see "Mailchimp" instead of "23.249.218.X".</li>
    <li><strong>Per-sender alignment status</strong>: a vendor with DKIM passing but not aligned shows up as a yellow row, not a green one. That's the actionable signal.</li>
    <li><strong>Trend dashboards</strong> per source so you can see "this vendor's failure rate doubled last week" before users notice.</li>
    <li><strong>Phase-by-phase guidance</strong>: pre-built filters for "what's currently failing DMARC?" &mdash; the list that drives your migration decisions.</li>
    <li><strong>DNS monitoring</strong> for the DMARC record itself, so accidental changes (someone fat-fingered <code>p=none</code> back on) trigger an alert.</li>
</ul>

